passages.text: Consumer | Food Retailing
Five Below, Inc  FIVE | \(\) 144.13\(In Line | Target Price / Base Case:\) \ \(150.00\) (Rmb \(\) 134.00)  Earnings Report
Company Statistics52-Week Range$52.38 - $146.66Base Case$150.00Upside/Downside3.9%Market Capitalization (M)$7,817Price/Earnings28.0Forward P/E26.7Dividend Yield0.0%Short Interest6.0%
1 Year Price History

Five Below is focused on the "boss" AKA the customer while delivering wow in its stores evidenced by the \(12\% +\) comp, \(9\%\) traffic, and \(50\%\) EBIT growth YoY. Five's turnaround has been remarkable, reflecting improved store execution (i.e. hour investment), simplification of price messaging/enhanced value, and trend right merchandising including KPOP/ Labubu / Super Squish etc.. Credit CEO Winnie Park and team for getting back to Five historic strength of wow merchandising and value. Risk remains from a volatile tariff backdrop - including 150- 250bps of EVR Est margin pressure in 2H from tariffs (pre offset), wage inflation, shrink, and a choppy consumer backdrop. We are raising our EPS by \(\) 0.30/6\%\(for'25 - 26 reflecting topline momentum & cost leverage. Our Base Case is raised to\) \ \(150\) or \(28x\) C26 EPS, yet we see upside constrained somewhat by tariffs in the current political climate. For those looking for unit growth SFM is our top Food Retail pick having pulled back to \(23.5x\) C26 EPS with high single digit sq ft growth/traffic gains of its own.

What we liked: Traffic. Trends. Marketing shift. CapEx tweaked down. Cash on hand. Five's \(8.7\%\) traffic drove the \(12\% +\) total comp, with a nice blend of new customers and wallet share from existing. It starts with merchandising and trend, and KPOP/Labubu should help deliver a comp of \(3\% +\) in holiday, in our view. That said, Five's marketing shift is subtle but meaningful in terms of going deeper into social including Tik Tok, YouTube and potentially more around Instagram. Five reduced its capex outlook slightly but still aiming for 150 stores this year. Party City locations - i.e. 30 of them - were targeted but actual costs are below plan. Five is dynamically responding to retail peer closures i.e. RAD/PRTY/TUES etc.. in a constructive way. Cash/Investments of \(\) 660m\(and no bank debt vs.\) \ \(1.7bn\) of operating lease liability.

What to watch: Tariff volatility. Wage inflation. Store hour investment. Incentive comp. Five Beyond. Tariffs are a moving target, up to \(\sim 19\%\) effective rate vs. \(3\%\) to start the year. Five is navigating a 150- 250bp likely headwind from tariffs with 200bps+ in F4Q. Product availability should remain solid for holiday, aided in part by early receipts. The full tariff impact is likely to be felt in '26 which creates a binary outcome for our '26 EPS model. Wage inflation remains \(3\% +\) broadly in retail and Five likely won't be immune. Adding store hours is right for the "boss", yet likely pressures margin in 2H and potentially '26 as well. Moving Five Beyond from its own back section to in- line will take labor. Incentive comp is a 150bp hit in 2Q which moderates to 70 and then 60bps by 4Q but still remains a hurdle.

Bottom Line: Five is leaning into newness, trend, and value to help mitigate a volatile tariff backdrop. 2Q results show their efforts are bearing fruit, evidenced by the \(12\% +\) comp, margin expansion and building cash war chest. Tariffs remain a wild card into '26, in our view, which we believe can constrain the near term upside. For growth investors that struggle with the supply chain uncertainty, we favor SFM having de- rated from \(30x+\) to \(23.5x\) CY26 EPS. SFM's comps are

decelerating, but we believe the value trend and healthy eating are secular drivers for share gain and margin expansion. For investors who want a discretionary kicker but do not want tariff risk, we like KMX to have a run toward \(\) 80\$ as it is poised to return to positive comps and we believe investors are largely offsides into their Sept. earnings call.

Traffic grows 4%, while basket builds. Shrink reverses and gross margins surge to record high 37%. EBIT margin recovers to 10% and the market eyes 12%+ over time. Topline growth at 15%+ w/ faster EPS growth helps the multiple recover.Back to playing offense/ working to regain trust. Comps hover come in closer to 3% in ‘26 with trend right merchandising, loyalty rollout, and discretionary mix coming back into vogue with an improving consumer backdrop all while unit demand elasticity comes in better than expected. EBIT Margin sits around 7.5 to 8% with enhanced scale and moderating wage inflation.Getting out “Shein”ed/Tag TEMUD. Comps languish at flat to 0.5%, or 350bps below pro COVID trend with share slip due to competition from TEMU & Shein & WMT. Gross margins fall 50-60bps to 35% on price pressure and deleverage. SG&A rate de-levers on wage inflation. EBIT margins dips to sub 7%. P/E at ~12-16x reflects a KR like valuation for a once high flier.

**What is the long term unit growth runway for FIVE?** FIVE operates 1.8k+ stores in 44 states. Management's target is 3.5k+ stores (raised from 2.5k at the March '22 analyst day), and expects to open up ~150 in '25 vs. '24 goal of 230. We believe DLTR's 8k+ stores illustrate that there is runway for 3.5k+ Five Below stores long term, as does Dollarama with 1.5k in a Canadian market ~1/10th the size of the U.S. The store payback period was around a year previously, but even if it is more like two years going forward it still offers strong returns.

**How will margins evolve with FIVE's effort to stabilize traffic and share?** FIVE should claw back fixed cost de-leverage, and EVR estimate 90bps of shrink headwind enabling EBIT margin to recover from 7-9% in CY25 toward 10-10.5% long term. Comps likely need to return to a steady 3% run rate to regularly lever. The 12% pre COVID run rate is unlikely to return, let alone the 13% COVID level peak. Traffic/share/comps will dictate the right run rate for EBIT margins, with the near term risk of further slippage into '25.

**What's the right multiple for FIVE?** In the past we used absolute and relative P/E vs. the market where FIVE averaged ~1.6-1.8x in the last five years, with a peak of 2.5-2.7x in late 2018 through April 2019 (pre Tariffs) and a trough around 0.5-1.3x. We now apply a 27-29x P/E as turnaround effort gains traction but tariff pressure constrains near term upside, in our view. FND's high 30s valuation and SFM/OLI/Boot growth peers in the 22-28x range show potential for re-rating when/if cyclical headwinds of tariffs abate.
1. It's just a trend away... Five is a fast second when it comes to solid merchandising once trends emerge.
2. Pilots like Helium could gain traction
3. A robust loyalty program/ personalization initiatives could accelerate share gain
4. Margins should improve from 1) normalizing comps 2) added scale and 3) ocean freight into '24 and beyond as shrink normalizes.
5. Store growth runway is sizeable. We see potential for ~2.5x Five's store footprint in the U.S. for top quintile unit growth potential
1. Competition rising Temu/Shein, reinvigorated Dollar Tree. Target adding sub $10 product as well.
2. The low end consumer defers discretionary purchases given lingering inflation headwinds
3. Wage inflation - we look for LSD-MSD + inflation.
4. Shrink headwinds could linger.

Evercore ISI's recommendations are based on a stock's total forecasted return over the next 12 months. Total forecasted return is equal to the expected percentage price return plus gross dividend yield. We divide our stocks under coverage into three primary ratings categories, with the following return guidelines:

Outperform- the total forecasted return is expected to be greater than the expected total return of the analyst's coverage sector. In Line- the total forecasted return is expected to be in line with the expected total return of the analyst's coverage sector. Underperform- the total forecasted return is expected to be less than the expected total return of the analyst's coverage sector. Coverage Suspended- the rating and target price have been removed pursuant to Evercore ISI policy when Evercore is acting in an advisory capacity in a merger or strategic transaction involving this company and in certain other circumstances. Rating Suspended- Evercore ISI has suspended the rating and target price for this stock because there is not sufficient fundamental basis for determining, or there are legal, regulatory or policy constraints around publishing, a rating or target price. The previous rating and target price, if any, are no longer in effect for this company and should not be relied upon.
Prior to October 10, 2015, the "Coverage Suspended" and "Rating Suspended" categories were included in the category "Suspended."

FINRA requires that members who use a ratings system with terms other than "Buy," "Hold/Neutral" and "Sell" to equate their own ratings to these categories. For this purpose, and in the Evercore ISI ratings distribution below, our Outperform, In Line, and Underperform ratings can be equated to Buy, Hold and Sell, respectively.
